<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="36" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,647,422,725]" pageId="3" pageNumber="36">
DISTRIBUTION AND HABITAT. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="36">
— 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Calyptranthera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="3" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schatziana">Calyptranthera schatziana</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[489,535,453,479]" pageId="3" pageNumber="36">type</typeStatus>
locality at the Masoala Peninsula in the northeastern part of 
<collectingCountry box="[113,250,515,541]" name="Madagascar" pageId="3" pageNumber="36">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
. It was found in humid evergreen forest on laterite at 
<quantity box="[344,404,545,572]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="36" unit="m" value="50.0">50 m</quantity>
altitude in flower in November. It differs from all other species of the genus by its well-developed thread-like and somewhat club-shaped prolonged connectives in combination with very small and erect cylindric corona lobes, which do not exceed the thecae.
</paragraph>
